Task.Name: Initiation Phase
Task.Notes: Note: This template is for illustration purposes only. In the real world, project phases often overlap each other during the closedown of one phase and preparation for the next phase.

Task.Name: Project Charter Development
Task.Notes:
A Charter:
(1) helps Management understand what the project will deliver, its business justification, and a high level estimation of the time, cost and resources required (2) serves as a commitment by Management to dedicate the time and resources necessary to prepare a more detailed, written "Project Plan" for formal funding approval; (3) should be relatively brief -- averaging around 3-5 pages in length.
Note: Too much detail in the Charter can detract from a clear, concise business reason why Management should allow a project to go beyond the "Initiating" phase. There are also many unknowns at this stage of the ballgame that can make detailed time, cost and resource projections very risky. Projections in too much detail early on can contribute to serious cost and schedule overruns later in the project.

Task.Name: Document summary of business purpose justification
Establish high-level time, cost, and resource estimates
Project Plan Development
Task.Notes:
A written "Project Plan" (not a work plan schedule):
(1) is a formal, approved document used to manage and control project execution (2) provides a detailed review of project time, cost, scope, resources, risk and other controls necessary for Management to approve all required funding and staffing (3)is expected to change over time as more accurate information becomes available; hence, the importance of change control.
The Project Charter, which becomes part of the overall Project Plan, should remain relatively stable over time, and serve as Management's reference guide as to why the project exists.

Task.Name: Create scope description (based on business objectives)
Define scope boundaries (both in and out of scope)
Define key project deliverables (including user-acceptable criteria)
Create WBS to work-level execution
Task.Notes: WBS can ideally be completed at the fourth level of breakdown, but should not exceed five levels.

Task.Name: Create schedule baseline (with expected resource effort)
Task.Notes: Base the schedule baseline on the time and resource effort needed to achieve project milestones and deliverables. A formal change control should be applied with a pre-determined threshold limit (e.g., 10% over original estimate requires formal Management approval before a new baseline can be established).

Task.Name: Define budget baseline (with schedule and cost assumptions)
Task.Notes: The Budget Baseline should be driven by the Schedule and other cost assumptions. A pre-determined threshold limit should also be defined (e.g., 10% over the original Budget requires formal Management approval before the new Baseline is allowed).

Task.Name: Establish baseline tolerance thresholds (trigger change control)
Project Milestones (PMs)
Task.Notes: Recommend not more than 10 to 15 major milestones per project with an average duration of 60 days or less per milestone.

Task.Name: Define standard PM and approval gates
Document WBS, milestones, and deliverables (dates and resourcing)
Name project team members (with roles and responsibilities)
Define all project stakeholders (with roles and project team liaison)
Create org chart: project team, sponsor, steering committee, stakeholders
Document change control procedure for budget and schedule baselines
Document change control for approved scope baseline
Document change control for systems modifications
Document risk process: prioritization, mitigation, and contingency guidelines
Document risk assessment for scope, budget, and schedule baselines
Document issues process: prioritization, resolution, and tracking guidelines
Document formal 3-tiered escalation: project manager, sponsor, and executives
Document guidelines: project updates and stakeholder collaboration
Document guidelines for document repository access and controls
Document standard project team and executive status report guidelines
Define criteria for user-acceptance testing (with checklist)
Define criteria and process for periodic stakeholder satisfaction survey
Identify method of survey (phone, in-person, Internet, magazines, etc.)
Establish process for archiving project data
